\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Measuring and explaining job creation and job separation rates is a fundamental part of labor economics (Mortensen 1970,
 Pissarides 1985,
 Mortensen and Pissarides,
 1994).
 Transition rates between labor market states can be calculated using data on gross flows in an unrestricted way.
 In some countries,
 statistical offices publish labor market flows based on panel datasets,
 such as the Labor Force Survey (LFS) in the European Union and the Current Population Survey (CPS) in the United States.
 A limitation of the panel method is that the data are not representative of the general population,
 and flows constructed from it are not consistent with aggregate stocks computed from the full cross-section.
 This problem can be treated using 
\emph on
statistical methods
\emph default
 (Frazis et al.,
 2005),
 but these do not make use of the logic of the underlying 
\emph on
economic
\emph default
 processes.
 Unfortunately,
 for many countries,
 gross flows data are not reported,
 and it is hard or impossible to acquire the original micro-level panel dataset.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A possible way out is the approach of Casado,
 Fernandez és Jimeno (2015),
 using cross-sectional microdata with retrospective information on labor market status.
 This method allows for the measurement of flows,
 but only at the annual frequency and is likely to be contaminated by measurement error due to recall.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An alternative method widely used in the literature is to concentrate on 
\emph on
employment
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
unemployment
\emph default
 only,
 and approximate job separation and job creation rates by unemployment inflow and outflow rates (Shimer 2005).
 Shimer's method is based on the assumption that the participation decision can be ignored and that job to job transitions are not important,
 therefore data on unemployment duration is sufficient to calculate the rates of interest.
 Despite the questionable assumptions,
 the method is popular,
 perhaps because it is straightforward anduses publicly available data on unemployment duration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recently both the empirical literature on labor flows,
 and the macro literature on business cycles (Elsby,
 Hobijn and Sahin 2015;
 Campolmi and Gnocchi 2014) have questioned the omission of inactivity.
 Research in labor economics has been looking at the differences between unemployment and out of the labor force status (see an overview in Dunson and Stone,
 2017).
 Also,
 Krause and Lubik (2006) and Karahan et al.
 (2017) provide evidence the importance of job to job transitions,
 especially in booms.
 This idea has reflections also in research on labor market transitions.
 Hobijn and Sahin (2009),
 in particular,
 used job tenure information to compute the job separation rate.
 However,
 they use unemployment duration data for the job finding rate.
 This is in line with their maintained two-state assumption and is likely to miss important dynamics.
 Also,
 their estimation method is relatively complex,
 making it a less likely candidate for widespread adoption than that of Shimer (2015).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This paper overcomes the limitations,
 but retains the practical simplicity of the approach of Shimer (2015).
 It provides a straightforward method for the estimation of job finding- and job separation rates based on job tenure data.
 The method is consistent with both job to job transitions and the structure provided by the search and matching model
\emph on
,

\emph default
 yielding also a 
\emph on
search participation rate
\emph default
.
 The method has the added benefit of using only openly available data,
 often at the quarterly frequency
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Hobijn and Sahin (2009) and Casado,
 Fernandez és Jimeno (2015) work on annual frequency
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 We illustrate the use of the method by applying it to data from Canada and the United Kingdom.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In what follows,
 we first outline a simple model leading to employment flow equations and show identification based on that.
 Then we discuss alternative measures and thirdly,
 we introduce the data we use and provide empirical results to illustrate our approach.
 Finally we discuss the possibility for further identification based on the data we have at hand.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Labor flows from job tenure:
 a model and identification
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Shimer (2005) shows how to compute unemployment inflow and outflow rates using data on the unemployment rate and on unemployment duration.
 He interprets these as the 
\emph on
job finding rate
\emph default
 and the 
\emph on
job separation rate
\emph default
.
 In the basic search and matching model (Pissarides 2000,
 Chapter 1) these two rates determine changes in unemployment and employment since the labor force participation decision is not taken into account.
 However,
 if three labor market states are relevant instead of two,the concepts of job finding and job separation are wrongly identified from unemployment dynamics and this approach is not sufficient to correctly identify the relevant transition rates.
 This section shows how to overcome this restriction in a straightforward and consistent way.
 In particular,
 using information on 
\emph on
inactivity
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
job tenure,

\emph default
 besides that on employment and unemployment,
 along with some structure imposed by theory,
 makes it possibleto identify key transition probabilities relevant for macroeconomic- and labor market analysis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Employment flows
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our model assumes that time is discrete,
 but the model frequency can be arbitrarily high.
 Data is available at a quarterly frequency,
 but it is possible that over a quarter at least workers experience multiple transitions.
 This is the well-known time aggregation problem,
 introduced into the labor flow literature by Shimer (2005).
 While Shimer treated the problem using a continuous time framework,
 our setup is more conducive to discrete time methods,
 applicable to the daily frequency,
 the highest realistic one.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To fix ideas,
 we will assume that decisions are made daily,
 and we aggregate these daily flows into quarterly probabilities.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 denote the start of the current quarter,
 and we use the index 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 to index days within a quarter.
 There are 
\begin_inset Formula $T=365/4$
\end_inset

 days in a quarter (we ignore leap years and the minimal differences that come from the unequal lengths of months).
 The crucial assumption - in line with the literature - is that the daily flow rates are constant over a quarter.
 This allows us to derive the changes in stocks between the beginning of two quarters,
 and identify the underlying flow rates from quarterly data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{t+\tau-1}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{t+\tau-1}$
\end_inset

,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{t+\tau-1}$
\end_inset

 denote shares of employment,
 unemployment,
 and the inactive (not in the labor force) 
\emph on
in the population
\emph default
 at the end of period 
\begin_inset Formula $t+\tau-1$
\end_inset

.
 A 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{t}$
\end_inset

 fraction of the formerly employed lose their jobs at the beginning of period 
\begin_inset Formula $t+\tau$
\end_inset

 (recall that transition rates are constant within a quarter).
 Therefore,
 the population share of 
\emph on
potential
\emph default
 job searchers at 
\begin_inset Formula $t+\tau$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{t}e_{t+\tau-1}+u_{t+\tau-1}+i_{t+\tau-1}$
\end_inset

.These include the previously unemployed who stay in the labor force,
 the previously inactive who return to the labor force,
 and also those who change jobs within the period.
 The timing assumption for changing jobs allows us to account for job-to-job transitions,
 which is likely to be quantitatively important for job churning.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This setup was used,
 for example,
 in Campolmi and Gnocchi (2016).
 They incorporate labor market search and the participation decision into an otherwise standard New Keynesian framework.
 Their focus on monetary policy and inflation.
 They do not explore the measurement implications of the labor market setup,
 which is the main contribution of our paper.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Out of this pool,
 a fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{t}$
\end_inset

 decides to look for a job.
 The number of searchers is thus given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s_{t+\tau}=\lambda_{t}\left(\rho_{t}e_{t+\tau-1}+u_{t+\tau-1}+i_{t+\tau-1}\right).\label{eq:threes}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

It is important to emphasize that we 
\emph on
do not assume an equal search participation rate
\emph default
 for all types of searchers.
 Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:threes"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) defines 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{t}$
\end_inset

 as an average rate,
 and it is perfectly compatible with different participation rates for the unemployed,
 inactive,
 and job changers.
 The main point is that while we cannot identify these rates separately,
 we can calculate an average as we show below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t}$
\end_inset

 of the searchers (
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t}s_{t+\tau}$
\end_inset

 fraction of the total population) finds jobs during the period.
 Again,
 
\emph on
this is an average rate
\emph default
,
 and rates for different groups can - and are likely to - differ from each other.
 We can only calculate the number of new jobs relative to the searching population,
 which yields 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t}$
\end_inset

 as an average job finding rate.
 Unsuccessful searchers become 
\emph on
unemployed
\emph default
:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u_{t+\tau}=\left(1-f_{t}\right)s_{t+\tau}.\label{eq:threeu}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Potential job searchers who chose not to participate are inactive:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
i_{t+\tau}=\left(1-\lambda_{t}\right)s_{t+\tau}=\left(1-\lambda_{t}\right)\left(\rho_{t}e_{t+\tau-1}+u_{t+\tau-1}+i_{t+\tau-1}\right).\label{eq:threei}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using these definitions,
 the flow equation of employment is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e_{t+\tau}=\left(1-\rho_{t}\right)e_{t+\tau-1}+f_{t}s_{t+\tau}.
\]

\end_inset

After substituting for the share of searchers and rearranging,
 the equation becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
e_{t+\tau}=\lambda_{t}f_{t}+\left(1-\rho_{t}\right)\left(1-\lambda_{t}f_{t}\right)e_{t+\tau-1}.\label{eq:threee}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we use this equation to solve for the employment rate at 
\begin_inset Formula $t+T$
\end_inset

,
 which is the start of the next quarter.
 To simplify notation,
 let us define 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{t}=\lambda_{t}f_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{t}=\left(1-\rho_{t}\right)\left(1-\lambda_{t}f_{t}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 One can think about the first as the job finding rate of a random person in the potential searcher population (that is:
 taking into account the probability of participation),
 while the latter gives the share of those with stable employed status between the periods.
 Then the following derivation links 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{t+T}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{t}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
e_{t+T} & =\eta_{t}+\varphi_{t}e_{t+T-1}\\
 & =\eta_{t}+\varphi_{t}\left(\eta_{t}+\varphi_{t}e_{t+T-2}\right)\\
 & \vdots\\
 & =\eta_{t}\sum_{\nu=0}^{T-1}\varphi_{t}^{\nu}+\varphi_{t}^{T}e_{t}\\
 & =\frac{\eta_{t}}{1-\varphi_{t}}\left(1-\varphi_{t}^{T}\right)+\varphi_{t}^{T}e_{t}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Substituting back the original rates,
 we get the following flow equation for quarterly employment:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
e_{t+T} & =\frac{\lambda_{t}f_{t}}{1-\left(1-\rho_{t}\right)\left(1-\lambda_{t}f_{t}\right)}\left\{ 1-\left[\left(1-\rho_{t}\right)\left(1-\lambda_{t}f_{t}\right)\right]^{T}\right\} \nonumber \\
 & +\left[\left(1-\rho_{t}\right)\left(1-\lambda_{t}f_{t}\right)\right]^{T}e_{t}\label{eq:empl}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly,
 we can also derive how the number of the inactive changes between two quarters.
 Using eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:threei"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:empl"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) and the identity that 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{t+\tau}+u_{t+\tau}+i_{t+\tau}=1$
\end_inset

,
 we can write this as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
i_{t+T} & =\left(1-\lambda_{t}\right)\left(\rho_{t}e_{t+T-1}+1-e_{t+T-1}\right)\nonumber \\
 & =1-\lambda_{t}-\left(1-\rho_{t}\right)\left(1-\lambda_{t}\right)e_{t+T-1}\nonumber \\
 & =\left(1-\lambda_{t}\right)\left\{ 1-\left(1-\rho_{t}\right)\left[\frac{\eta_{t}}{1-\varphi_{t}}\left(1-\varphi_{t}^{T-1}\right)+\varphi_{t}^{T-1}e_{t}\right]\right\} ,\label{eq:inact}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{t}$
\end_inset

 are defined as above.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Identification
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we are ready to discuss the identification of the three flow rates,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{t}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 Information on job tenure includes the share of the newly employed (
\begin_inset Formula $e_{t}^{s}$
\end_inset

),
 whose tenure is less than one quarter.
 Using the simple fact that those employed in 
\begin_inset Formula $t+T$
\end_inset

 are composed of those employed through the period and of the newly employed,,
 the job separation rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{t}$
\end_inset

 is directly identified as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(1-\rho_{t}\right)^{T}=\frac{e_{t+T}-e_{t+T}^{s}}{e_{t}}.\label{eq:threerho}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The right-hand side is the fraction of those who are employed at the beginning of the current quarter,
 and remain employed at the same job by the beginning of the next quarter.
 The left-hand side defines this as the probability that a job survives over the 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 periods within the quarter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next,
 we can use eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:empl"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) to solve for the product 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{t}=\lambda_{t}f_{t}$
\end_inset

,
 given quarterly data on employment and the job separation rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{t}$
\end_inset

 calculated from eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:threerho"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 For any 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

,
 this is a simple non-linear equation that can easily be solved numerically.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{t}f_{t}$
\end_inset

 are sufficient to calculate the auxilliary variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{t}=\left(1-\rho_{t}\right)\left(1-\lambda_{t}f_{t}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Using these in eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:inact"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 along with quarterly employment and inactivity data,
 we can solve for the search participation rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 Finally,
 the job finding rate is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t}=\eta_{t}/\lambda_{t}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The quarterly job finding and job separation probabilities can easily be calculated from the high-frequency rates:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
F_{t} & =1-\left(1-f_{t}\right)^{T}\label{eq:F}\\
R_{t} & =1-\left(1-\rho_{t}\right)^{T}.\label{eq:R}
\end{align}

\end_inset

The first equation is the probability that someone who is searching for a job at the beginning of the current quarter finds one by the next quarter (assuming that she does not give up search earlier).
 The second equation defines the survival probability of a job from the current quarter to the next.
 Note that we do not need to adjust the search participation rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{t}$
\end_inset

,
 since it is (by assumption) a constant ratio of stocks within a quarter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The identified rates and probabilities are sufficient to calibrate a macroeconomic model of 
\emph on
employment
\emph default
.
 To understand macroeconomic aggregates (GDP,
 inflation,
 etc.),
 employment and its associated flows are the key labor market variables.
 As we noted earlier,
 however,
 the job finding rate 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t}$
\end_inset

 (along with the search participation rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{t}$
\end_inset

) is an 
\emph on
average
\emph default
 among job searchers with different labor market backgrounds.
 Flows for individual groups (such as the unemployed) are of great interest to social policy,
 but are less relevant for the 
\emph on
macro modeler
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our method,
 due to the timing assumption that searchers may find and start work within one period,
 incorporates job-to-job transitions.
 This is important since much of the churning in employment is due to these transitions (Mukoyama,
 2014),
 which data on stocks or even gross flows fail to capture.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The source of new information - some intuition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To see where the new information comes in our procedure with respect the the existing,
 two-state one,
 using unemployment duration data,
 it is worth discussing the intuition behind the identification further.
 First,
 let us recall the key equations between periods 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t+1$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
e_{t+1} & =\left(1-\rho_{t}\right)e_{t}+f_{t}\lambda_{t}\left(\rho_{t}e_{t}+1-e_{t}\right)\\
i_{t+1} & =\left(1-\lambda_{t}\right)\left(\rho_{t}e_{t}+1-e_{t}\right)\\
\left(1-\rho_{t}\right)e_{t} & =e_{t+1}-e_{t+1}^{s},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

this latter identifying the job separation rate directly.
 Using the link between the three labor market states,
 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{t+1}=1-e_{t+1}-u_{t+1}$
\end_inset

,
 in the second equation,
 we can write that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{t}\left(\rho_{t}e_{t}+1-e_{t}\right)=e_{t+1}+u_{t+1}-\left(1-\rho_{t}\right)e_{t}.
\]

\end_inset

Substituting this back into the first equation yields
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e_{t+1}=\left(1-\rho_{t}\right)e_{t}+f_{t}\left[e_{t+1}+u_{t+1}-\left(1-\rho_{t}\right)e_{t}\right].
\]

\end_inset

Finally,
 using the third equation for the job separation rate above,
 we can express the job finding rate as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f_{t}=\frac{e_{t+1}^{s}}{e_{t+1}^{s}+u_{t+1}}.\label{eq:niceident-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The derivation above assumes that the population 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{t}=E_{t}+U_{t}+I_{t}$
\end_inset

 is constant between two periods.
 Even if this is reasonable both at daily and quarterly frequency,
 the calculations can be easily extended to include population change.
 Using capital letters for levels and denoting the size of the population with 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{t}$
\end_inset

,
 one obtains
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{t}=\frac{E_{t+1}^{s}}{E_{t+1}^{s}+U_{t+1}-(P_{t+1}-P_{t})},
\]

\end_inset

which is the pool of searchers adjusted with population change,
 almost equivalent to the earlier result.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An important implication of these calculations is that while we worked with a three-state setup,
 most of the extra information comes directly from the use of short-term employment data.
 The intuition is that the short-term employed come from all states,
 including inactivity,
 thus their number carries more relevant information than that of the short-term unemployed.
 An added benefit of our approach is the ability to account for job to job transitions,
 as the number of short-term employed include those coming from another job.
 Neither of these is true of the approach of Shimer (2005) and the use of data on short-term unemployment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although the above did not consider time aggregation directly,
 equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:threerho"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) does not depend on the assumed frequency if the population is stationary and one can show that the difference is small in any case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Alternative measures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To facilitate comparison of our identified quarterly probabilities,
 we also calculate alternative measures used in the literature.
 Below we briefly discuss the usage of gross flow data (whenever available) and unemployment duration data,
 and how to correct these for time aggregation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Data on gross flows
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One obvious way to calculate quarterly probabilities is to use labor flow data.
 Although subject to time aggregation,
 flow data reveal more details,
 since one can see all six possible transitions among the three labor market states.
 Job-to-job flows,
 however,
 cannot be calculated from flow data without further breakdown - this is an advantage of our method that relies on job tenure information.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We follow Shimer (2012) to calculate quarterly probabilities from gross flow data,
 correcting for time aggregation using the high frequency approach of the previous section.
 Let us define the matrix of daily transition probabilities - assumed constant within a quarter - as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
m_{t} & =\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
1-m_{t}^{EI}-m_{t}^{EU} & m_{t}^{IE} & m_{t}^{UE}\\
m_{t}^{EI} & 1-m_{t}^{IE}-m_{t}^{IU} & m_{t}^{UI}\\
m_{t}^{EU} & m_{t}^{IU} & 1-m_{t}^{UE}-m_{t}^{UI}
\end{array}\right].
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Also,
 let 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{t+\tau}$
\end_inset

 be the following matrix:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n_{t+\tau}=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
n_{t+\tau}^{EE} & n_{t+\tau}^{IE} & n_{t+\tau}^{UE}\\
n_{t+\tau}^{EI} & n_{t+\tau}^{II} & n_{t+\tau}^{UI}\\
n_{t+\tau}^{EU} & n_{t+\tau}^{IU} & n_{t+\tau}^{UU}
\end{array}\right].
\]

\end_inset

A typical element of 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{t+\tau}$
\end_inset

 is people who started period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 in labor market position 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

,
 and are in labor market position 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $t+\tau$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j=E,I,U$
\end_inset

.
 It is clear that within a quarter,
 the evolution of 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{t+\tau}$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n_{t+\tau+1}=m_{t}n_{t+\tau}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To correct for time aggregation,
 one needs to calculate the transition matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{t}$
\end_inset

 from the quarterly flows.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{t}$
\end_inset

 denote the matrix of observed flows,
 where the elements are normalized into shares using the sum of possible flows from a given state.
 Then given regularity conditions that hold in our data,
 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{t}$
\end_inset

 can be diagonalized.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{t}=p_{t}\mu_{t}p_{t}^{-1},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{t}$
\end_inset

 is a matrix with the eigenvectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{t}$
\end_inset

 in its columns,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{t}$
\end_inset

 is a diagonal matrix with the eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{t}$
\end_inset

 along the diagonal.
 Then the daily transition matrix is simply given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m_{t}=p_{t}\mu_{t}^{\frac{1}{T}}p_{t}^{-1}.
\]

\end_inset

With the daily transition matrix we calculate the adjusted quarterly probabilities as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\rho_{t}^{gf} & =1-\left(m_{t}^{EE}\right)^{T}\\
f_{t}^{gf} & =1-\left[1-\frac{m_{t}^{UE}u_{t}+m_{t}^{IE}i_{t}}{\left(m_{t}^{UE}+m_{t}^{UU}\right)u_{t}+\left(m_{t}^{IE}+m_{t}^{IU}\right)i_{t}}\right]^{T}\\
\lambda_{t}^{gf} & =\frac{\left(m_{t}^{UE}+m_{t}^{UU}\right)u_{t}+\left(m_{t}^{IE}+m_{t}^{IU}\right)i_{t}}{u_{t}+i_{t}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Two states with unemployment duration data
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most widely used method to calculate transition probabilities from stock data was proposed in Shimer (2005).
 This method uses data on unemployment duration to calculate unemployment inflow and outflow probabilities,
 correcting for time aggregation.
 Since the procedure is described in detail in the original article,
 we keep the exposition brief.
 The only difference is that instead of continuous time,
 we derive the equations using our previous high frequency assumption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The quarterly unemployment outflow probability (interpreted as the job finding rate) is calculated as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
F_{t}^{ts} & =1-\frac{u_{t+1}-u_{t+1}^{s}}{u_{t}},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{t}^{s}$
\end_inset

 is the number of those who have been unemployed for less than a quarter at the beginning of the next quarter.
 The daily unemployment inflow rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{t}^{ts}$
\end_inset

 (interpreted as the job separation rate) is then calculated from the following equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{t+T}=\frac{\rho_{t}^{ts}}{\rho_{t}^{ts}+f_{t}^{ts}}\left[1-\left(1-\rho_{t}^{ts}-f_{t}^{ts}\right)^{T}\right]+\left(1-\rho_{t}^{ts}-f_{t}^{ts}\right)^{T}u_{t},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t}^{ts}=1-\left(1-F_{t}^{ts}\right)^{\frac{1}{T}}$
\end_inset

.
 Finally,
 the quarterly job separation rate is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{t}^{ts}=1-\left(1-\rho_{t}^{ts}\right)^{T}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

