\begin_layout Section
Discussion:
 group-level identification
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we stressed above,
 the identified job finding rate is an average over the various groups that make up job searchers.
 These groups are the formerly unemployed,
 the formerly inactive,
 and those changing jobs.
 There is no reason why the job finding probabilities should be the same for these three sub-groups.
 Unfortunately stock data with job duration information is not sufficient to identify group-level transition rates.
 The question is whether it is possible to impose additional restrictions on the flow rates to identify the separate probabilities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that there is one additional time series that we have not used so far.
 In particular,
 Shimer ( 2005) uses unemployment duration data (see below) to calculate unemployment outflow and inflow rates.
 Although he interprets the outflow rate as a job finding probability,
 this is not accurate,
 since some of those who leave unemployment become inactive.
 Our question in this section is whether adding unemployment duration to our list of observables is useful to calculate separate job finding rates for the three groups of searchers,
 and if not,
 what additional restrictions might be needed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The answer to the first question is no.
 The additional information allows us to calculate the unemployment outflow rate,
 as shown by Shimer (2005).
 Without knowing how many of the unemployed remain active,
 we cannot separately calculate the job finding rate of the unemployed.
 Unless we assume that the search participation rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the same for each subgroup,
 we cannot go further.
 This assumption is unlikely to hold in the data,
 since it is likely that the search participation rate of the currently unemployed (
\begin_inset Formula $u_{t}$
\end_inset

) is higher than the search participation rate of the currently inactive (
\begin_inset Formula $i_{t}$
\end_inset

),
 i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{t}^{u}>\lambda_{t}^{i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To study the second question,
 let us impose - contrary to the above - a set of identification restrictions to eliminate heterogeneity across different groups.
 In particular,
 let us assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t}^{u}=f_{t}^{e}=f_{t}^{i}\left(=f_{t}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{t}^{u}=\lambda_{t}^{e}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\left(=\lambda_{t}^{eu}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The assumptions mean that the job finding rate is independent of previous labor market status,
 and the search participation rate is the same between the formally employed and the formally unemployed.
 We do allow for lower search intensity among the inactive relative to the other two groups of potential searchers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is easy to verify that under these assumptions all flows are identified.
 Compared to the previous case we need to compute one additional indicator,
 which is the probability that an inactive becomes an active searcher (
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{t}^{i}$
\end_inset

).
 Let us write down the flow equation of unemployment,
 using the identification restrictions:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u_{t+1}-u_{t}=\rho_{t}\lambda_{t}^{eu}\left(1-f_{t}\right)e_{t}+\lambda_{t}^{i}\left(1-f_{t}\right)i_{t}-\underbrace{\left[1-\lambda_{t}^{eu}\left(1-f_{t}\right)\right]}_{\phi_{t}}u_{t}.\label{eq:ident-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Using data on unemployment duration we can calculate the outflow rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 Substituting this into equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ident-1"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) we can also compute the unemployment inflow rate.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In this section we ignore time aggregation and focus only on identification at the baseline frequency.
 Time aggregation would complicate the calculations,
 but would not change the identification results.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Given our previous estimates for the job finding rate 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t}$
\end_inset

,
 the job destruction rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{t}$
\end_inset

,
 and the average search intensity 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{t}=\left(\rho_{t}e_{t-1}+u_{t-1}\right)\lambda_{t}^{eu}+i_{t-1}\lambda_{t}^{i}$
\end_inset

,
 we can recover the two separate search intensities,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{t}^{eu}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{t}^{i}$
\end_inset

.
 This means that we would have all the necessary information to reproduce the gross flows among all three states.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unfortunately,
 this identification strategy does not work in practice.
 The simple reason for this is that the unemployment outflow rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{t}$
\end_inset

 tends to be smaller than the average job finding rate 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t}$
\end_inset

 (see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:uk"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 This is inconsistent with eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ident-1"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 which requires that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{t}>f_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 Our strong identification restrictions cannot be maintained:
 the job finding rate of the unemployed is apparently lower than average.
 Reasons for this can be the better labor market position of the newly unemployed and job changers,
 or that people returning from inactivity might find it easier to get a job,
 or probably a combination of both.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we relax the 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t}^{e}=f_{t}^{u}=f_{t}^{i}$
\end_inset

 assumption,
 full identification is no longer possible,
 since we would need to calculate at least five rates from four time series.
 Either we find new data,
 or we introduce some other restrictions.
 There are no obvious choices in either direction,
 hence we do not see full identification possible from aggregate data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Conclusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We presented a method to estimate key labor market transition rates using publicly available data on employment,
 unemployment,
 inactivity and job tenure.
 The method is easy to implement and improves measurement compared to methods that ignore movements into and out of inactivity.
 Data are more broadly available than direct measures of labor market flows,
 and stock-flow consistency is not an issue.
 Finally,
 the method takes into account job-to-job transitions that are important in understanding employment dynamics,
 in particular over the business-cycle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We highlight two topics for further research.
 First,
 longer job tenure time series are available at the annual frequency.
 These can be utilized combining the current methodology with the techniques developed in Hobijn and Sahin (2009).
 Second,
 a more detailed comparison of our results with gross flows may lead to improvements in the raking procedure used to ensure stock-flow consistency in the latter.
\end_layout

